<problem>
  <p>Continually flip a biased coin with 0.6 probability to land on head until a tail occurs. Let X denote the number of flips.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>What is \(P(X\le 3)\)?</li>
  </ul>
  <numericalresponse answer="0.784">
    <responseparam type="tolerance" default="0.001"/>
    <formulaequationinput/>
    <solution>
      <div class="detailed-solution">
        <p>Explanation-1</p>
        <p>\(P(X\le 3)\) = \(1 - P(X\gt 3)\). \(X > 3\) implies first 3 flips must be head. Therefore, \(P(X\gt 3)\) = \(0.6^3\) and \(P(X\le 3)\) = \(1 - 0.6^3\) = 0.784</p>
        <p>Explanation-2</p>
        <p>\(P(X\le 3)\) = \(P(X=1)+P(X=2)+P(X=3)\) = 0.4 + 0.6 * 0.4 + 0.6 * 0.6 * 0.4 = 0.784</p>
        
      </div>
    </solution>
  </numericalresponse>
  <ul>
    <li>What is \(P(X\ge 5)\)?</li>
  </ul>
  <numericalresponse answer="0.1296">
    <responseparam type="tolerance" default="0.001"/>
    <formulaequationinput/>
    <solution>
      <div class="detailed-solution">
        <p>Explanation</p>
        <p>\(P(X\ge 5)\) = \(P(X\gt 4)\) = \(0.6^4\) = 0.1296</p>

      </div>
    </solution>
  </numericalresponse>
</problem>
